  <!-- Q_ -->
  <h2 id="q-factory">Q_ — Quantity Factory</h2>
  <div class="api-card">
    <div class="api-signature"><span class="api-name">Q_</span><span class="api-args">(value, unit, uncertainty=None)</span></div>
    <p>The primary entry point. Creates a <code>Quantity</code> from a value and unit string.</p>
    <h4>Parameters</h4>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>value</code></td>
          <td><code>float | int | ndarray | Tensor | Array | str</code></td>
          <td>The numeric value. Accepts scalars, array-like (NumPy, PyTorch, JAX), or a string like <code>"10 m/s"</code>.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>unit</code></td>
          <td><code>str | CompoundUnit | None</code></td>
          <td>Unit expression. Required if value is not a string. Supports <code>/</code>, <code>*</code>, <code>^</code>, SI prefixes, and named units.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>uncertainty</code></td>
          <td><code>float</code></td>
          <td>Optional 1&sigma; standard deviation. Defaults to <code>0.0</code> (no uncertainty).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>symbol</code></td>
          <td><code>str | None</code></td>
          <td>Optional symbolic name for tracing (advanced use).</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <h4>Returns</h4>
    <p><code>Quantity</code> — a unit-aware wrapper around the value.</p>
    <h4>Example</h4>
    <pre><code>from physure import Q_

# Scalar
v = Q_(10, "m/s")

# With uncertainty
g = Q_(9.81, "m/s^2", uncertainty=0.02)

# NumPy array
import numpy as np
arr = Q_(np.array([1, 2, 3]), "km")

# PyTorch tensor
import torch
t = Q_(torch.tensor([1.0, 2.0]), "kg")</code></pre>
  </div>

  <!-- Quantity -->
  <h2 id="quantity">Quantity</h2>
  <div class="api-card">
    <div class="api-signature"><span class="api-kw">class</span> <span class="api-name">Quantity</span></div>
    <p>Core class representing a physical quantity. Instances are typically created via <code>Q_()</code>.</p>

    <h4>Properties</h4>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>.magnitude</code></td><td><code>float | ndarray | ...</code></td><td>The raw numeric value. This is the primary way to access the number.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.m</code></td><td><code>float | ndarray | ...</code></td><td>Shorthand alias for <code>.magnitude</code> (pint-compatible).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.unit</code></td><td><code>CompoundUnit</code></td><td>The attached physical unit.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.u</code></td><td><code>CompoundUnit</code></td><td>Alias for <code>.unit</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.uncertainty</code></td><td><code>float | Numeric</code></td><td>Standard deviation (1&sigma;), returns <code>0.0</code> if none set.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.dimension</code></td><td><code>Dimension</code></td><td>Dimensional signature (e.g. [length&sup2;]).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.symbol</code></td><td><code>str | None</code></td><td>Optional symbolic name for tracing.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h4>Methods</h4>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Returns</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>.to(unit_str)</code></td><td><code>Quantity</code></td><td>Returns a new Quantity converted to the given unit string. Raises <code>IncompatibleUnitsError</code> if units are incompatible.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.to_base()</code></td><td><code>Quantity</code></td><td>Returns a new Quantity in SI base units (m, kg, s, A, K, mol, cd).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.diff(var)</code></td><td><code>Quantity</code></td><td>Symbolic differentiation. Requires <code>[symbolic]</code> extra. <code>var</code> is a Quantity with symbolic magnitude.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.__add__, __sub__</code></td><td><code>Quantity</code></td><td>Addition/subtraction. Raises <code>IncompatibleUnitsError</code> if units are incompatible.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.__mul__, __truediv__</code></td><td><code>Quantity</code></td><td>Multiplication/division. Combines units automatically.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.__pow__(n)</code></td><td><code>Quantity</code></td><td>Power. <code>Q_(2, "m") ** 3</code> → <code>8 m³</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.dot(other)</code></td><td><code>Quantity</code></td><td>Computes dot product for vector quantities.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.cross(other)</code></td><td><code>Quantity</code></td><td>Computes cross product for vector quantities.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h4>Class methods</h4>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>Quantity.from_input(value, unit, ...)</code></td><td>Alternative constructor. Use when you need finer control over the system or backend.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h4>Example</h4>
    <pre><code>from physure import Q_

F = Q_(100, "N")
A = Q_(0.5, "m^2")
P = F / A

print(P)           # 200.0 Pa
print(P.to("kPa")) # 0.2 kPa
print(P.unit)      # Pa
print(P.dimension) # [mass·length⁻¹·time⁻²]
print(P.magnitude) # 200.0 (raw numeric value)</code></pre>
  </div>

  <!-- Uncertainty -->
  <h2 id="uncertainty">Uncertainty</h2>
  <div class="api-card">
    <div class="api-signature"><span class="api-kw">class</span> <span class="api-name">Uncertainty</span></div>
    <p>Abstract base class for uncertainty models. In practice you pass a <code>float</code> as the <code>uncertainty</code> argument to <code>Q_</code> — physure automatically wraps it in the appropriate model based on the active propagation mode.</p>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Property / Method</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>.std_dev</code></td><td>The standard deviation (1&sigma;).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.variance</code></td><td>Not always available directly — access via <code>VarianceModel.variance</code>.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>.vector_slice</code></td><td>Slice into the covariance matrix (for correlated/vectorized mode).</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <pre><code>from physure import Q_

# Pass a float directly — it is auto-wrapped internally
q = Q_(9.81, "m/s^2", uncertainty=0.02)
print(q.uncertainty)       # 0.02 (std dev)
print(q.uncertainty**2)    # ~0.0004 (variance manually)</code></pre>
  </div>

  <!-- Module Functions -->
  <h2 id="module-functions">Module-level functions</h2>
  <p>These are all importable directly from <code>physure</code>:</p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Function</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>get_current_system()</code></td><td>Returns the active UnitSystem.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>get_unit(expr)</code></td><td>Parses and returns a Unit object from an expression string.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>propagation_mode(mode)</code></td><td>Context manager to switch between uncertainty propagation modes: <code>"correlated"</code> (default), <code>"uncorrelated"</code>, <code>"monte_carlo"</code>, <code>"unscented"</code>.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>uncertainty_mode(mode)</code></td><td>Context manager for the uncertainty computation backend.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>system_context(system)</code></td><td>Context manager to use a custom UnitSystem (aliased as <code>use_system</code> internally).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>create_system(config)</code></td><td>Creates a UnitSystem from a config name (e.g. <code>"imperial.conf"</code>).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>create_default_system()</code></td><td>Creates and returns the default SI-based UnitSystem.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>save_state(path, quantities)</code></td><td>Serializes quantities to disk (requires <code>[io]</code> extra).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>load_state(path)</code></td><td>Deserializes quantities from disk (requires <code>[io]</code> extra).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>jit(fn)</code></td><td>Decorator/function to JIT-compile a unit-aware function.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>propagation_mode example</h3>
  <pre><code>import physure as mk
from physure import Q_

# Default is 'correlated' — x - x = 0 exactly
x = Q_(5.0, "m", uncertainty=0.1)
delta = x - x
print(delta.uncertainty)   # ~0.0  (correlated cancellation)

# Switch to uncorrelated mode
with mk.propagation_mode("uncorrelated"):
    delta2 = x - x   # 0.0 ± 0.141 m  (errors add in quadrature)

# Other modes: "monte_carlo", "unscented"
with mk.propagation_mode("monte_carlo"):
    ...</code></pre>

